.TH RULES 1
.SH NAME
rules \- evaluate harmonic correctness of realized continuo chords

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B rules

.SH DESCRIPTION
.I rules
is a filter that reads a stream of realized musical groups from standard
input and evaluates them against voice-leading and harmonic rules.
It uses a sliding window of size 4 to check transitions between chords
. For each group, the program outputs a result line
indicating if it passes (OK) or fails (FAIL).

.SH INPUT FORMAT
The program expects "group" lines, typically from a realization engine.
A group line must start with
.B GROUP
and contain these space-separated fields:

.TP
.B ID:\fIn\fR
Decimal integer identifier for the group.
.TP
.B passing
(Optional) Marks the group as a passing chord.
.TP
.B BASS_ACTUAL:\fIpitch\fR
Simplified pitch name used for interval calculations.
.TP
.B REALIZATION:\fIp1/p2/...\fR
Slash-separated LilyPond pitches for inner voices.
.TP
.B MELODY:\fIpitch\fR
One or more LilyPond pitches for melody notes.

Lines starting with
.B LESSON
,
.B //
, or empty lines are echoed unchanged.

.SH VALIDATION RULES
The following rules are applied to each non-passing group:

.IP \(bu 4
.B Parallel Fifths and Octaves:
Checks for parallel motion into perfect fifths or octaves between ALL
voice pairs (Bass, Inner, Melody) across consecutive groups.
.IP \(bu 4
.B Bass Tritone Leap:
The bass may not move by a diminished fifth or augmented fourth (6
semitones mod 12) between groups.

.SH OUTPUT FORMAT
For every group, the program prints a single line to standard output:

.B RESULT \fIID\fR OK
.br
if all rules pass.

.B RESULT \fIID\fR FAIL \fImessage\fR
.br
if a rule is violated, with a description of the error.

.SH EXIT STATUS
Returns 0 on success.

.SH AUTHOR
Written by Jakob Kastelic (2026).
